\nTo prove this point, M. E. Coyle, j\nexecutive rice president of Gen\neiw? Motors, testified before the\nsubcommittee the other day: \"In\n&S\u00c4\u00c4Brw!.fiLS\u00c4\nrLftTStl 'ti\u00c4\n-i has the value the customer gets for\nhis automobile dollar been affected\nfrom a long-term viewpointr\n\n\u2022l\ntry.\n\nj\nAnswering liia own question, af\nter he bad satisfied the inveatiga-\ntors on numerous points in several\nhours on the'witness stand, Mr. i\nv Coyle the committee mem-,\nhers outside to view a recondition\n_-- -Sj and\nIan\ni\nMaimfacturer's list price of Buick\n-----Chevrolet,\nuiwpH fho\ned 1929 Buick four-door sedan\na 1948 Chevrolet four-door sedan.\ntn 1929 was 1020; i948 Chevrolet.\n\"'^1080. Mr. Ooyie also showed the\nCongressmen how the 1948 Chevro\nlet offers more for the dollar than\nthe 1929 Buick\u2014more horsepower.!\ngreater speed, increased fuel eco\nnomy, more safety and comfort,\nfeatures, etc.\n\"It should be pointed out.\" Mr.\nCoyle emphasised, \"that the manu\nfacturer'\u00bb Hat price for both cars\nexcludes freight, Uxes and dealer!\nhandling. The Buick price did not\ninclude the spare tire and bumpers\nwhic\u00a3 are included in the Chevro\nlet price.\" Then he listed the many\nnew features which the 1948 Chev\nrolet price includes but which were\nnot available on the 1929 Buick.\nThe witness also brought out\nthat while in 1928 it took an aver-\nr age factory worker nearly 1,200\nt hours to earn the price of a Chev-\nt rolet. today It takes.less than 1,000\n-c hours. He added that in 1939. when\nfarm prices were low, it took cash\nreceipts from the sale of eight beef\nsteers to buy a Chevrolet. Today\nthe same number of steers would\nt bring the price of two Chevrolet\u00bb.\nCommenting on the exhibit in\nhearings the next day. Senator\nO'Mahoney. Democrat of Wyoming,\nrailsd it \"a prvtljr clear demonalra\ntkm that modern technology has\nresulted in producing far more per\ndollar than was ever produced be\nfore by industry.\n